In contrast, the N K-edge spectra clearly vary among the different samples. A reduced intensity of the π∗ resonances at 399 and 402 eV is evident in the spectra of the nanocubes compared to the nanotubes, whereas the intensity of the σ∗ shows opposite behavior. On the other hand, no significant differences are observed when comparing the same nanostructures with different thicknesses (see Fig. 2). The different peak ratios σ∗ vs π∗ suggest that the electronic configuration of nitrogen in the nanocubes is different from that adopted in the nanotubes. Graphitic-like nitrogen has been reported for carbon nanostructures containing less than 4 atomic % N [56,58], whereas pyridine-like nitrogen configurations are observed in layers containing more than 8 atomic % N [56–58,60]. XPS measurements have revealed the surface nitrogen content of the samples presented here to reach approximately 8 atomic % N (see Table 2). According to literature, at this concentration pyridine-like N configurations should dominate (see Fig. 4
                     ). However, the XRS data at the N K-edge (compare Fig. 2, right panel) consistently show the presence of the two peaks (at 399 and 402 eV), implying the presence of both graphitic-like and pyridinic-like nitrogen, both sp2 nitrogen, in all of our samples. This is also confirmed by the relative abundances derived by curve-fitted XPS N1s spectra (see Table 3
                     , and Fig. 4). In fact, it is possible to observe that the most abundant contributions are due to graphitic-like (peaks having an energy range comprised between 399.2 and 399.6 and between 400.6 and 401.6 eV [65]) and pyridinic-like (398.3–398.5 eV [66]) nitrogen, both hybridized sp2. In Fig. S1, Table S1 and Fig. S5 and Table S2 are reported results of fitting of high-resolution C1s and O1s XPS spectra, respectively. In C1s results it is observed that there are many contributions. Moreover, considering that the error for the percentages is 1 % and for the binding energies is 0.1 eV, there are statistically no differences between the samples. In O1s high-resolution region two contributions are found for nanocubes, CO and C–O–C, while in nanotubes another contribution is added, O from adsorbed water. The amount of CO and C–O–C is similar in all the samples, except for Thin NC. This behavior shows that C = X in Table S1 for this sample is largely due to CN rather than CO.
